According to [Facebook documentation|https://developers.facebook.com/docs/reference/opengraph/object-type/article], publishers should populate the article:author meta tag in their pages with a URL to the author's Facebook page. 

As such, we have customers building their pages with tags like this:
{code}
<meta property="article:author" content="https://www.facebook.com/heygregr" />
{code}

And we are then storing the URL as the "author" in our content profile for the page:
{code}
$ python cx.py /document/search '{"siteIds":["1145186158190231305"],"query":"query(url:\"http://www.1077theend.com/blogs/gregr/i-went-reptile-zoo-monroe\")"}'
{
  "totalCount": 1, 
  "matches": [
    {
      "id": "23b93f33f79190b27a5440e066970f65d6445ff0", 
      "siteId": "1145186158190231305", 
      "score": 9.628432, 
      "fields": [
        {
          "field": "author", 
          "value": [
            "https://www.facebook.com/heygregr"
          ]
        }
       ]
    }
  ]
}
{code}

To allow users to support this FB functionality while also giving us the ability to store an actual author name instead of a URL, we need a prioritized meta field (such as {{cXenseParse:author}}) that will be used in place of, or in addition to, the URL values we get from the article:author value.
